      <acqinfo id="aspace_10e6dd2aa8a5b76f455ef19846e4f412">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Gift of the Jewish Board of Family and Children's Services, 1990.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_bc80dae7987d211e11476962bf702610">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The records are restricted until October 25, 2065, after which the records will be made available in accordance with the Yale University Library's regulations and policies. Written authorization from the Jewish Board of Family and Children's Services, which maintains the exclusive authority to grant or deny requests, is required to access the materials. Requests may be made to the Board by an email sent to mssa.assist@yale.edu and will be forwarded. You will be contacted directly by the Board regarding your request. In making your request, please be as specific as possible about your project, your plans for using the collection, and the specific materials to which you seek access.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <bioghist id="aspace_613d7c52d98ea2a91361fdab254926a0">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The Jewish Board of Family and Children's Services is a New York City-based organization, which was begun in the late nineteenth century. It serves people of all religions and cultures. The organization focuses on psychiatric counseling, conflict mediation, and managing grief.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_94469b6ff23bd3cf9d4f23e19c16df77">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The materials consist of adoption study records.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <processinfo id="aspace_6d408ac7c5a52f0a94d01dc47b9bc62d">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Former title: Jewish Board of Family and Children's Services Adoption Study Records</p>  
      </processinfo>
      <userestrict id="aspace_8e42880aa160f11056b02b60bf8a2794">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>Copyright is retained by the creator(s) of this collection for materials they have authored or otherwise produced.  On October 18, 2065, copyright passes to Yale University.  Copyright status for other collection materials is unknown.  Transmission or reproduction of materials protected by U.S. Copyright Law (Title 17, U.S.C.) beyond that allowed by fair use requires the written permission of the copyright owners.  Works not in the public domain cannot be commercially exploited without permission of the copyright owners. Responsibility for any use rests exclusively with the user.</p>  
      </userestrict>
